In the case of pristine C-dots (
                        Figure S3
                     ), the corresponding Raman spectra exhibited typical D and G bands with ID/IG ratio of 0.89, reflecting a nearly equal presence of both disordered and graphitic carbon structures. However, in the case of CuO-Cdot-2.5, the ID/IG ratio dropped to 0.93, suggesting an increase in graphitic character[47]. This trend continues as the C-dots content increased to 8 % and 16.6 %, with corresponding ID/IG ratios of 0.86 and 0.82, respectively, indicating a progressive increase in graphitization. This could be attributed to the influence of the CuO nanostructure's catalytic properties, which presumably promoted the organization of carbon into more graphitic structures, or potentially the structural templating effect of CuO[48]. The slight graphitization of C-dots over CuO can play a critical role in controlling the electrochemical response of CuO-Cdots for glucose oxidation. A relatively graphitized C-dots could provide the CuO scaffold with improved charge-transferability and stability by limiting the surface passivation facilitating electrocatalytic oxidation of glucose[49]. Moreover, the combination of disordered carbon with slight graphitization would provide a greater density of active sites for electro-oxidation, thereby improving the signal generation capability of the sensors and, therefore, the sensitivity of the electrode[50].
